<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl:
```c
int32 OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl(const OS_object_token_t *token, OS_module_prop_t *module_prop)
{
    /*
     * Limiting strictly to POSIX-defined API means there is no defined
     * method to get information about a module contents.
     *
     * The "dlinfo()" function might return some interesting information
     * but this is actually a non-posix extension / platform-defined API.
     *
     * This returns success - although there is no information to add here,
     * the parent/shared layer information is still valid.
     */
    return OS_SUCCESS;
}
```
</target_code>
<additional code>Here are the definitions of symbols that are related to the target function OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl:
#define OS_SUCCESS (0)
...
int32 OS_ModuleInfo(osal_id_t module_id, OS_module_prop_t *module_prop)
{
    OS_common_record_t *         record;
    OS_module_internal_record_t *module;
    int32                        return_code;
    OS_object_token_t            token;

    /* Check parameters */
    OS_CHECK_POINTER(module_prop);

    memset(module_prop, 0, sizeof(OS_module_prop_t));

    return_code = OS_ObjectIdGetById(OS_LOCK_MODE_GLOBAL, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, module_id, &token);
    if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS)
    {
        record = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_global_module_table, token);
        module = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_module_table, token);

        strncpy(module_prop->name, record->name_entry, sizeof(module_prop->name) - 1);
        strncpy(module_prop->filename, module->file_name, sizeof(module_prop->filename) - 1);

        return_code = OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl(&token, module_prop);

        OS_ObjectIdRelease(&token);
    }

    return return_code;
}
...
typedef struct OS_object_token OS_object_token_t
...
typedef struct
{
    cpuaddr             entry_point;
    cpuaddr             host_module_id;
    char                filename[OS_MAX_PATH_LEN];
    char                name[OS_MAX_API_NAME];
    OS_module_address_t addr;
} OS_module_prop_t
</additional code>

explanation:
No unreachable code fragments were found in the provided code. Analysis details:
- OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl contains only a comment block and a single return statement (return OS_SUCCESS;). There is no code following the return, so there are no unreachable statements inside this function.
- OS_ModuleInfo: control flow is explicit — parameter checks, memset, a call to OS_ObjectIdGetById, and an if (return_code == OS_SUCCESS) block. All statements in the success branch (reading records, strncpy calls, calling OS_ModuleGetInfo_Impl, and OS_ObjectIdRelease) are reachable when the condition is true; the final return return_code is reachable in both success and failure cases. There are no early returns, goto statements, or other constructs that would render any following statements unreachable.
- The provided macros, typedefs, and struct definitions do not introduce executable code and therefore cannot be the source of unreachable code.
- No switch statements, loops with guaranteed-exit-before-body, or duplicated return paths that would leave code after a return/goto unreachable were present in the snippets.

Given the supplied code fragments, there is no code that appears unreachable and therefore nothing to flag under MISRA C 2023 Rule 2.1.
